		<header>
			
			<h1>South Africa diversifying its trade away from the EU</h1>

			
			<h4>
												06 October 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>Against the background of the pending EU–South Africa Summit, the South African Revenue Service (SARS) has revealed that South Africa is now less reliant on the EU and US market than formerly. In the past 5 years, South African exports to Asia have surged from 26% of total exports to 35%. However exports to the EU have fallen from 34% of the total in the first half of 2006 to 27% of the total in the first half of 2011.</p><p>IMF figures in June 2011 projected growth rates for emerging and developing economies three times as large as those of advanced economies (6.6% compared to 2.2% for 2011). In the coming period, ‘the world economy will depend on emerging markets to drive growth’. China is now a major trade partner for South Africa, with in 2010 exports up 36% on the previous year.</p><p>However the SARS notes the continuing dependence of South Africa on exports of natural resources, which is even more pronounced in the country’s trade with Asian economies. Minerals, base metals, precious metals and stones account for 83% of South Africa’s exports to Asia, while they represent only 55% of exports to the EU and 58% of exports to the USA.</p><p>Currently, India is seeking to deepen its trade relations with the SACU, COMESA and ECOWAS, with Indian Trade Minister Anand Sharma maintaining that an India–SACU trade deal is possible by the end of 2011. Annual trade between India and Africa has increased fifteenfold in the past 10 years according to Minister Sharma (from US$3 billion in 2000 to US$46 billion in 2010. India hopes that bilateral trade with South Africa will reach US$15 billion before the end of 2014.</p><p>These factors need to be seen against the background of calls from South Africa’s Trade Minister Rob Davies for reform of the SACU so that it can ‘serve as a platform for engagement in trade relations’ with developing countries that will be responsible for most of the global growth in the years ahead. Minister Davies called for more collaboration on ‘industrialisation, agroprocessing businesses, and value addition’.</p><p>Meanwhile, in July 2011 it was announced that the Namibian and Chinese governments had reached agreement ‘on sanitary and phyto-sanitary export requirements’. It is expected that Namibian agricultural and livestock products will ‘enter the Chinese markets in the foreseeable future’. The Namibian government is seeking to move away from exports of unprocessed agricultural products to exports of more value-added products. Indeed, in July 2011 the Namibian Ministry of Finance announced ‘a new tax system that would penalise exports of raw materials’, with the aim of establishing ‘an economic strategy anchored in beneficiation of minerals and value addition to natural resources through partnerships and joint ventures’.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
