<a href="http://www.tralac.org/2011/08/31/india-south-africa-trade-to-touch-15-billion-before-2014/" target="_self">http://www.tralac.org/2011/08/31/india-south-africa-trade-to-touch-15-bi...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The South African Revenue Service figures highlight underlying EU concerns about the future security of raw materials supplies. The demand of newly emerging economies in Asia for raw materials is particularly strong, with these economies taking an even higher percentage of their imports from South Africa in the form of raw materials than the EU. This accounts for the EU’s determination to maintain the MFN clause in the SADC–EU EPA, which obliges South Africa to grant the same trade treatment to the EU that it grants to advanced developing countries.</p><p>The MFN clause is viewed quite differently in South Africa, where it is seen as placing a needless constraint on negotiators in their dealings with rapidly growing advanced developing country economies, in their efforts to try to move beyond the traditional pattern of raw material exports.</p><p>For both parties the issue of the MFN clause is seen as critical. However more progress might be made if the underlying concerns of each party were directly addressed. In the case of South Africa, their aim is to structurally transform their engagement with the global economy, to move away from an excessive dependence on raw materials exports. If the EU were to include in the EPA firm commitments to promoting investments in South Africa to support such a structural transformation, then the underlying South African concern could be addressed, in a context where geographical diversification on its own is proving ineffective in fostering the desired structural transformation.</p><p>In the case of EU concerns, South Africa could strengthen its commitments to negotiating equal treatment for EU exports outside the context of a binding MFN clause, while deepening economic cooperation in the critical areas of EU concern (e.g. ensuring supplies of critical raw materials for industrial processors).</p>
		</div>
		
